# API Patterns

## View conventions

- Public views: inherit from `generics.ListAPIView` / `RetrieveAPIView`, set `permission_classes = [AllowAny]`
- Authenticated views: inherit from `generics.ListCreateAPIView` / `RetrieveUpdateDestroyAPIView`, set `permission_classes = [IsAuthenticated]`
- Always scope user-owned data: `get_queryset` must filter by `user=self.request.user`
- Use `get_object_or_404` with compound lookups (slug + number) instead of pk for content endpoints

## Serializer conventions

- Use `source=` to map snake_case model fields to camelCase JSON keys
- Include `_dbId` (mapped from `pk`) when the frontend needs to reference a record
- Keep serializers flat — avoid deep nesting beyond one level
- Use `SerializerMethodField` for computed values like `chapter_count`

## URL conventions

- Public content: `/api/subjects/`, `/api/subjects/<slug>/`, `/api/subjects/<slug>/chapters/<int:number>/`
- Authenticated resources: `/api/highlights/`, `/api/notes/`
- Auth endpoints: `/api/auth/register/`, `/api/auth/login/`, `/api/auth/token/refresh/`, `/api/auth/me/`

## Filtering

- Use query params for list filtering: `?subject=slug&chapter=number`
- Parse in `get_queryset`, not in the serializer
- Return empty list (not 404) when no matches

## Error responses

- Use DRF's built-in error formatting (400 with field-level errors)
- Custom errors: return `Response({"detail": "message"}, status=XXX)`
- Never expose internal details (tracebacks, SQL) in error responses
